    "summary": "The Anglo-Japanese Alliance, first concluded in January 1902 and renewed in 1905 and 1911, was the first formal alliance between a Western power and an Asian nation on terms of equality. It provided each party with assurance of neutrality if the other went to war with one power, and mutual military assistance if either faced two or more opponents. The alliance grew from shared concerns: Britain sought to check Russian expansion in East Asia without the expense of maintaining a large naval presence there, while Japan sought international recognition and a powerful backer for its ambitions on the Asian continent.\n\nThe alliance had significant consequences. It gave Japan diplomatic confidence to challenge Russia in the Russo-Japanese War of 1904–1905, knowing Britain would not allow France to enter the war on Russia's side. Japan's victory over Russia became a landmark moment in world history, the first modern defeat of a major European power by an Asian state. During World War I, Japan honored the alliance by entering on the Allied side and seizing German possessions in the Pacific and China. The alliance was allowed to lapse in 1921–1923 under American pressure, reflecting the new geopolitical realities of the Pacific after the war.",
